  "prompt": "When is 70% isopropyl rubbing alcohol better than 91%?",
  "response": "70% isopropyl rubbing alcohol is often considered better than 91% for several specific applications due to its effectiveness and safety.\n\n1. **Disinfection**: 70% isopropyl alcohol is more effective as a disinfectant compared to 91% isopropyl alcohol. This is because the higher water content in 70% alcohol slows evaporation, allowing the alcohol to remain in contact with the surface longer, which increases its antimicrobial effectiveness. The water also helps break down the cell walls of bacteria and viruses, allowing the alcohol to penetrate and kill the microorganisms more effectively.\n\n2. **Skin Use**: 70% isopropyl alcohol is generally safer for use on the skin compared to 91% alcohol. The higher concentration of 91% can be more irritating and drying to the skin, while 70% is gentler and less likely to cause irritation.\n\n3. **Household Cleaning**: For general household cleaning, 70% isopropyl alcohol is typically sufficient and safer for many surfaces. It can effectively clean and disinfect without the higher risk of damage associated with stronger concentrations.\n\n4. **Medical Settings**: In medical settings, 70% is typically used for disinfecting instruments and skin prior to injections or minor procedures because it strikes a balance between effectiveness and safety.\n\nUsing 70% isopropyl rubbing alcohol ensures a potent disinfectant effect while minimizing potential damage or irritation.",
